issue.body:
This PR implements a configurable "manual translation timing" feature that can be enabled per-target to perform OCR and translation only on the first user-initiated capture, skipping processing for subsequent frames until capture is restarted.

## Changes Made

### Settings Integration
- **TargetSettings.cs**: Added `IsManualTranslationTiming` boolean property with default value `false`
- **AllSettingsViewModel.cs**: Added UI property for the setting in the "Misc" category
- **Settings saving/loading**: Integrated the new setting into the save/load workflow

### UI Enhancement
- **PropertyGrid**: New checkbox appears in Target-specific Settings under "ãã®ä»–" (Misc) section
- **Localization**: Added translations for all supported languages:
  - æ—¥æœ¬èª: "ç¿»è¨³ã‚¿ã‚¤ãƒŸãƒ³ã‚°ã®æ‰‹å‹•åŒ–ã‚’æœ‰åŠ¹ã«ã™ã‚‹"
  - English: "Enable manual translation timing" 
  - Deutsch: "Manuelle Ãœbersetzungszeit aktivieren"
  - í•œêµ­ì–´: "ìˆ˜ë™ ë²ˆì—­ íƒ€ì´ë° í™œì„±í™”"
  - And more for Vietnamese, Chinese (Simplified/Traditional)

### Core Logic Updates
- **MainViewModelBase.cs**: Modified to read the setting and only apply first-capture-only behavior when enabled
- **Conditional processing**: OCR and translation skipping only occurs when the setting is explicitly enabled
- **Event handling**: CaptureStarted event resets the flag only when the feature is active

## Behavior

**When disabled (default):**
- Application works normally, processing all frames
- No change in existing behavior

**When enabled:**
1. First user-initiated frame triggers OCR and translation processing
2. Subsequent frames are skipped until capture is restarted
3. Processing load is reduced significantly after initial recognition

**Per-target configuration:**
- Each translation target can have this setting configured independently
- Setting is saved in user configuration and persists across application restarts

This implementation provides the requested functionality as a configurable option rather than hardcoded behavior, allowing users to choose when to enable the performance optimization through manual control of translation timing.

Fixes #428.

Signed-off-by: Igor Bezukh <ibezukh@redhat.com>

Runbook PR: https://github.com/openshift/runbooks/pull/318

**What this PR does / why we need it**:
In an upgrade scenario it can happen that duplicate wasp-agent
deployment can appear, since previous wasp-agent deployments
were manual and in a different namespace.
Therefore in order to make sure the user is aware of it we
are adding an alert which will rely on the a metric of memory
overcommit percentage and presence of wasp namespace.

issue.body:
Hello,

I noticed that when running `cargo check` on this repository, a warning appeared:

```
warning: the following packages contain code that will be rejected by a future version of Rust: wl-clipboard-rs v0.7.0
```

This implies that wl-clipboard-rs should be updated to a newer version or this library will not compile in some future release of Rust.

comment.body:

No problem! Just one other thing that I noticed: the demos generate compiler warnings because `pixels_per_point` is not used, it can be fixed by telling the compiler to ignore the value with `pixels_per_point: _` - also I believe that the two demos basically now just do the same thing (the only difference being the auto-generated texture and shape being displayed in the background) so I think it would be appropriate to remove the `textures` demo.

But yeah, I think that since these are just changing the examples it probably doesn't need a version bump once those changes are implemented.

Rename IXL_QUESTION_COMPLETED to EXERCISE_COMPLETED throughout codebase

- Renamed message type from IXL_QUESTION_COMPLETED to EXERCISE_COMPLETED
- Updated result message type from IXL_QUESTION_COMPLETION_RESULT to EXERCISE_COMPLETION_RESULT
- Changed IPC handler from handle-ixl-question-completion to handle-exercise-completion

- Updated all related comments and console log messages
- Maintained functionality while improving naming clarity and generality

Fix App.tsx to use new onExerciseCompleted function name

- Updated function call from onIxlQuestionCompleted to onExerciseCompleted
- Updated handler function name from handleIxlQuestionCompleted to handleExerciseCompleted
- Updated variable name from ixlCompletionCleanup to exerciseCompletionCleanup
- Updated comments to reflect exercise completion instead of IXL-specific naming
- Resolves TypeError: window.ipcRenderer.onIxlQuestionCompleted is not a function

Refactor session management: move saveSessionToFile to electron main process

- Removed saveSessionToFile and sendSessionViaPostMessage from ixl-specific.js
- Removed endCurrentSession function (functionality moved to showCompletionAlert)
- Updated showCompletionAlert to send full session data via EXERCISE_COMPLETED
- Removed old save-ixl-session IPC handler from ipc-handlers.ts
- Removed IXL_SESSION_DATA handling from webview-preload.js
- Updated handle-exercise-completion to save session data to file
- QUESTION_CORRECT now only handles immediate feedback (sound, celebration)
- EXERCISE_COMPLETED now handles session saving and celebration
- Cleaner separation of concerns between immediate feedback and session persistence

Implement startSession flow with SESSION_STARTED message handling

- Updated startSession() to send SESSION_STARTED with {sessionId, start} format
- Added SESSION_STARTED handling in webview-preload.js to invoke trigger-session-start
- Added trigger-session-start IPC handler in ipc-handlers.ts
- Fixed TypeScript error by prefixing unused event parameter with underscore
- Build successful - ready for testing startSession functionality

Refactor session management: both start and completion write to same file

- trigger-session-start now creates session entry with {sessionId, start, status: 'active'}
- handle-exercise-completion now finds and updates existing session by sessionId
- Both methods use same file structure and logic for consistency
- Session entries are properly linked by sessionId throughout lifecycle
- File format: array of session objects with start/end timestamps and questions
- Build successful - ready for testing complete session lifecycle

Refactor: eliminate duplication by creating shared handleSessionFile function

- Created shared handleSessionFile() function for common file operations
- Both trigger-session-start and handle-exercise-completion now use shared logic
- Eliminated ~50 lines of duplicated code
- Function handles both 'start' and 'completion' operations
- Maintains same functionality while improving maintainability
- Build successful - code is cleaner and more maintainable

Rename session start to exercise start throughout codebase

- Changed SESSION_STARTED to EXERCISE_STARTED in all message types
- Updated trigger-session-start to trigger-exercise-start IPC handler
- Renamed handleSessionFile to handleExerciseFile for consistency
- Updated all variable names and comments from session to exercise
- Updated webview-preload.js and ixl-specific.js message handling
- Build successful - naming now makes more sense for IXL exercises

Update ixl-specific.js: change all session references to exercise

- Renamed variables: currentSession â†’ currentExercise, sessionQuestions â†’ exerciseQuestions

- Changed SESSION_ENDED to EXERCISE_ENDED message type
- Updated feedback handler names: handleSessionEndedFeedback â†’ handleExerciseEndedFeedback
- All console logs and error messages now use exercise terminology
- Build successful - consistent exercise terminology throughout ixl-specific.js

Simplify startExercise function: focus on basic exercise start only

- Removed complex exercise tracking logic from startExercise
- Function now simply generates sessionId and sends {sessionId, start}
- Eliminated question extraction, exercise object creation, and state management
- startExercise is now focused and single-purpose
- Build successful - cleaner, simpler function architecture

Implement correct exercise flow: first question starts exercise, subsequent questions only handle correct answers

- Added isFirstQuestion flag to track exercise state
- First /practice/pose: calls startExercise() AND handleCorrectQuestion()
- Subsequent /practice/pose: calls only handleCorrectQuestion()
- /practice/summary: calls endExercise() and resets isFirstQuestion flag
- Both fetch and XMLHttpRequest handlers updated with same logic
- Build successful - exercise flow now matches IXL behavior correctly

Update webview-preload.js and ipc-handlers.ts to match new message types

- Changed EXERCISE_COMPLETED to EXERCISE_ENDED in webview-preload.js
- Updated EXERCISE_COMPLETION_RESULT to EXERCISE_ENDED_FEEDBACK
- Changed sessionData to exerciseData in ipc-handlers.ts for consistency
- Updated success message from 'session saved' to 'exercise saved'
- All three files now use consistent EXERCISE_ENDED message flow
- Build successful - complete message type consistency achieved

Move trigger-question-correct IPC handler to ipc-handlers.ts

- Moved trigger-question-correct handler from success-feedback.ts to ipc-handlers.ts
- Added playSuccessSound function to ipc-handlers.ts for audio feedback
- Cleaned up success-feedback.ts to only contain interface definitions
- All IPC handlers now centralized in ipc-handlers.ts for better organization
- Build successful - centralized IPC handling architecture achieved

Refactor webview-preload.js to use pattern map for dynamic message handling

- Replaced repetitive if-else blocks with MESSAGE_PATTERNS map
- Added dataField mapping to handle different data field names (data vs feedbackData)
- Generic handleMessage function processes all message types dynamically
- Cleaner, more maintainable code - adding new message types only requires map update
- Reduced code duplication from ~80 lines to ~40 lines
- All three message types (EXERCISE_STARTED, QUESTION_CORRECT, EXERCISE_ENDED) now handled uniformly
- Build successful - pattern-based architecture implemented

Simplify MESSAGE_PATTERNS map by removing unnecessary dataField mapping

- Removed dataField property from all pattern entries since all messages use same structure
- All messages from ixl-specific.js have consistent {type, data} format
- Simplified handleMessage function to always use event.data.data
- Cleaner, more focused pattern map with only essential routing information
- Build successful - simplified architecture maintains functionality while reducing complexity

Implement dynamic string manipulation for IPC channels and feedback types

- Replaced static MESSAGE_PATTERNS map with dynamic string derivation
- IPC channels: 'trigger-' + messageType.toLowerCase().replace('_', '-')
- Feedback types: messageType + '_RESULT'
- Updated trigger-exercise-start to trigger-exercise-started for consistency
- All message handling now uses pure string manipulation - no configuration needed
- Adding new message types requires only adding to HANDLED_MESSAGE_TYPES array
- Build successful - ultimate DRY principle achieved with zero configuration

Fix currentExercise initialization and question tracking in ixl-specific.js

- Initialize currentExercise object in startExercise() function with sessionId, start time, status, and empty questions array
- Pass questionData parameter to handleCorrectQuestion() calls in both fetch and XMLHttpRequest interceptors
- Add question tracking logic in handleCorrectQuestion() to populate exerciseQuestions array
- Extract subject and gradeLevel from questionData for proper question information
- Fix 'No current exercise for correct question' error by ensuring currentExercise is properly initialized
- Build successful - exercise tracking now works correctly from start to completion

Fix handleCorrectQuestion function parameter definition

- Added questionData parameter to handleCorrectQuestion function definition
- Function was being called with data but parameter was missing from definition
- Resolves 'ReferenceError: questionData is not defined' error
- Build successful - question data now properly accessible in function scope

Fix QUESTION_CORRECT feedback loop and implement question counting in exercise files

- Prevent QUESTION_CORRECT_RESULT from being sent back to webview (causes feedback loop)
- Add 'question' operation type to handleExerciseFile function
- Change questions from array to number (count) in exercise entries
- trigger-question-correct now updates exercise file with question count increment
- Exercise start initializes questions: 0, each correct answer increments to 1, 2, 3, etc.
- Build successful - question tracking now properly updates JSON files with count

Add /practice/tally interception for real-time answer feedback

- Intercept /practice/tally requests to determine if answer was correct
- Check response for 'correct': true/false and show appropriate alert
- âœ… Correct! Great job! - for correct answers
- âŒ Incorrect. Keep trying! - for incorrect answers
- Added interception for both fetch and XMLHttpRequest methods
- Build successful - real-time answer feedback now working
